{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7bbe4752-425b-4bda-9983-abb4b4aaee49","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues to address before publishing:\n\n**🔴 Functional bug:**\n- The `Framework` symbol has no `replaces` property, so the chosen value will never be substituted into your project files (e.g., the `.csproj` `TargetFramework`). Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or whatever placeholder is in your source files).\n\n**🟡 Recommended for NuGet:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for tooling validation.\n- **Missing `description`** — important for discoverability on NuGet.org.\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — helps NuGet group related templates (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n- **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — typically `true` for project templates.\n\n**✅ Looks good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all properly set.\n\nIn short: **not quite ready** — the Framework parameter is non-functional, and you're missing metadata that NuGet.org relies on for display/search.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a5d2c0e-2615-48c7-a9d3-c6fdf494a5d6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but recommended for validation. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages so templates can be grouped properly.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0` but there's no `replaces` or `fileRename`** for the Framework symbol — The symbol is defined but doesn't seem to be wired to actually replace anything in the template files. \n\nWithout `replaces`, the framework choice won't actually substitute into the project file, so the parameter becomes inert.\n\n6. **Missing `description`** — Not strictly required but highly recommended for NuGet discoverability.\n\n7. **Missing `generatorVersions`** — Optional, specifies minimum template engine version.\n\nThe most critical gaps are the missing `$schema` and `description` fields, the Framework symbol lacking a `replaces` binding, and the absent `groupIdentity` and `preferNameDirectory` properties that are standard for NuGet templates.\n\nNow I'm narrowing down what would actually block this from being production-ready: the missing `description` hurts discoverability, the framework symbol's lack of `replaces` is a functional issue, and `$schema` should be included for validation purposes.","outputTokens":732,"requestId":"403C:1ECF:66413D1:72981D1:69EC1009"},"id":"81126060-4cde-4950-b628-ca80c1ff4de7","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:51:38.181Z","parentId":"2496f4e4-bb08-40a9-8449-f6379c0c16d0"}
